{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{Use British English|date=February 2018}} {{for|the 1975 accident at the same location|Dibbles Bridge coach crash}} {{Infobox bus accident |title=Dibble's Bridge coach crash (1925) |image=[[File:Dibbles bridge crash.jpg|300px]] |caption=A 1925 postcard showing the wrecked coach at the base of Dibbles Bridge. |date=10 June 1925 |location=Near [[Hebden, North Yorkshire]] |bus= |vehicles=1 |pax= |deaths=7 |injuries= |}}
'''The Dibble's Bridge coach crash''' was a fatal accident that occurred on 10 June 1925 on the B6265 road, at [[River Dibb|Dibble's Bridge]], below [[Grimwith Reservoir]] {{convert|1.6|mi|km}} east of [[Hebden, North Yorkshire|Hebden]], in the [[civil parish]] of [[Hartlington]] in [[Craven]], [[North Yorkshire]], England. Seven people were killed, and a number of others injured.
==Accident== The accident occurred when a coach carrying a party of members of the York Municipal Guild and their families on an outing to [[Bolton Abbey]] from [[York]] suffered brake failure as it travelled down a 1:6 (9.5°) (16.67%) gradient from Fancarl Top to the bottom of the valley downstream of [[Grimwith reservoir]]. It gained considerable speed and failing to negotiate the sharp bend at the bottom crashed through the parapet of Dibble's Bridge, landing on its roof. Many of the passengers were pinned beneath the vehicle, five being killed instantly, whilst two others died within half an hour. A number of other passengers were injured.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wheels of Industry|publisher=Commercial Motor|url=http://archive.commercialmotor.com/article/16th-june-1925/4/wheels-of-industry|accessdate=23 August 2014|date=16 June 1925}}</ref>
