{{distinguish|Employment fraud}}
'''Job fraud''' refers to fraudulent or deceptive activity or representation on the part of an [[employee]] or prospective employee toward an employer. It is not to be confused with ''[[employment fraud]]'', where an employer scams job seekers or fails to pay wages for work performed. There are several types of job frauds that employees or potential employees commit against employers. While some may be illegal under jurisdictional laws, others do not violate law but may be held by the employer against the employee or applicant.
== Résumé fraud == '''Résumé fraud''' or ''application fraud'' refers to any act that involves intentionally providing fictitious, exaggerated, or otherwise misleading information on a [[application for employment|job application]] or [[résumé]] in hopes of persuading a potential employer to hire an applicant for a job for which they may be unqualified or less qualified than other applicants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Combat Resume Fraud |url=http://www.inquestscreening.com/preemployment_background_Screeening_Combat_Resume_Fraud.asp |publisher=Inquest Pre Employment Screening |accessdate=2007-07-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302165400/http://www.inquestscreening.com/preemployment_background_Screeening_Combat_Resume_Fraud.asp |archivedate=2007-03-02 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Depending on the nature of the offense, the type of job, and the jurisdiction where it occurs, such an act may or may not be a violation of [[criminal law]].{{cn|date=April 2018}} In any case, knowingly providing inaccurate information to an employer or potential employer, if discovered by the employer, is almost always grounds for [[Termination of employment|immediate dismissal]] from the job or else denial of that job.
=== Effects ===
Almost half (48%) of organizations with fewer than 100 staff experienced problems with [[Vetting|vetted]] employees.
39% of UK organizations have experienced a situation where their vetting procedures have allowed an employee to be hired who was later found to have lied or misrepresented themselves in their application. <ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=http://www.onrec.com/content2/newsimages/SurveyPowerchex.pdf |title=Powerchex Annual Pre-employment Survey |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927120928/http://www.onrec.com/content2/newsimages/SurveyPowerchex.pdf |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>
=== Demographics === Younger, more junior people are more likely to have a discrepancy on their CV. Someone in a junior administrative position is 23% more likely to have a discrepancy on their CV than in a managerial role. An applicant aged under 20 is 26% more likely to have a discrepancy than a 51- to 60-year-old.<ref>[http://dofonline.co.uk/personnel/personnel-2007/drop-in-financial-job-applicant-frauds01807.html dofonline] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928081255/http://dofonline.co.uk/personnel/personnel-2007/drop-in-financial-job-applicant-frauds01807.html |date=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>
Neither men nor women are statistically more likely to have a discrepancy on their CV (X-squared = 0.56, df = 1, p-value = 0.46): 24% of applications submitted by women have a discrepancy compared to 26% of those for men.<ref name=":0" />
Graduates have marginally fewer discrepancies: 13% of their CVs contain a discrepancy compared to 17% of non-graduates.<ref>{{Cite news|title = A degree of creativity on CVs|url = http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/f5112740-56bb-11dd-8686-000077b07658.html#axzz3wJLg96qp|newspaper = Financial Times|date = 2008-07-21|access-date = 2016-01-04|issn = 0307-1766|first = David|last = Turner|first2 = Education|last2 = correspondent}}</ref>
