Originally the brainchild of Keith Feinstein, '''Videotopia''' is a travelling [[science museum]] exhibition documenting the history of [[video game]]s.  It is based on a larger collection of video game machines, now housed at [[The Strong]] in [[Rochester, New York]].<ref name="rochester"/>

==Collection==
It includes a wide range of commercial video arcade machines and game consoles, and also interactive [[multimedia]] kiosks containing information about the history of the games' development and their impact on popular culture. By 1996, the exhibit had had 20,000 attendees.<ref name="NGen21">{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Videogame Expo Goes Nationwide|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=September 1996|page=15}}</ref> In 1998, Feinstein's collection included 300 machines, and the touring exhibit had 75 of them.<ref name="forbes"/> By 2009 the touring exhibition included 100 machines, and the collection amounted to 15,000 items relating to video games.<ref name="rochester">Laura Keeney. "Play on, player". Rochester City Newspaper, July 8, 2009. http://www.rochestercitynewspaper.com/entertainment/family/2009/07/REVIEW-Videotopia/</ref>

Videotopia was operated by Feinstein's longtime curatorial partner Jeff Anderson, who maintained the exhibit's vast game collection, based in [[New Jersey]].{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}  Later Jon-Paul Dyson took over and the collection moved to the International Center for the History of Electronic Games at [[The Strong]] in [[Rochester, New York]].<ref name="rochester"/>

Videotopia has been featured at numerous science museums in the U.S., such as the [[Franklin Institute]] in [[Philadelphia]], as well as overseas and in selected performances of [[Video Games Live]].  Videotopia has been featured on television on [[CBS]]: [[The Early Show|This Morning]], the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]], [[CNN]], [[CNBC]], and many local television news programs{{citation needed|date=February 2012}} and written about in ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine,<ref name="forbes">Don Steinberg, "Giving Pac-Man his due", Forbes, March 23, 1998 https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1998/0323/6106184a.html</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'', [[Technology Review]], TICKET,{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} and ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]''.<ref name="NGen21"/>

